body:
Hi @lukasmasuch @Abdelgha-4

I have been investigating this issue and this problem was in fact caused by how the data is normalized when ```y_min``` and ```y_max``` are ```None```. Currently, the implementation assumes that the default value for ```y_min``` and ```y_max``` for every cell are ```0``` and ```1``` respectively whereas the expected behavior â€” [according to the argument description](https://docs.streamlit.io/develop/api-reference/data/st.column_config/st.column_config.barchartcolumn) â€” is that each cell should use its own minimum and maximum values. That's why negative numbers are not correctly displayed in the columns. I have already implemented a fix, but some unit tests in file ```ChartColumn.test.ts``` are now failing because they assume  ```y_min = 0``` and ```y_max = 1``` by default.

In particular it fails on test:

```s
  it("supports configuring min/max scale", () => {
    const mockColumn = getLineChartColumn()
    const mockCell = mockColumn.getCell([-100, 0, 100])
    // Default min/max scale is 0/1 so the values should be normalized:
    expect((mockCell as SparklineCellType).data?.values).toEqual([0, 0.5, 1])
```
This test expects default normalization to be based on ```[0, 1]```, but with the fix, it should be normalized based on the actual min/max of every cell.

And on the same test it fails here as well:

```s
    const mockColumn6 = getLineChartColumn({
      y_min: undefined,
      y_max: -100,
    })
    const mockCell6 = mockColumn6.getCell([-100, 0, 100])
    // min and max need to be defined, so this should be an error cell:
    expect(isErrorCell(mockCell6)).toEqual(true)
```
This tests assumes that because y_min is undefined the cell should be an error cell. In fact when the cell is created, since ```y_min = undefined``` ,  ```y_min``` is actually assigned to a default value. Currently this value is ```0``` as it is shown in this section from ```ChartColumn.ts``` file:

```s
function BaseChartColumn(
  kind: string,
  props: BaseColumnProps,
  chart_type: "line" | "bar" | "area"
): BaseColumn {
  const parameters = mergeColumnParameters(
    // Default parameters:
    {
      y_min: 0,
      y_max: 1,
    },
    // User parameters:
    props.columnTypeOptions
  ) as ChartColumnParams
``` 

Then ```y_min``` will be set to ```0``` and ```y_max``` will be set to ```-100```, and it will return and error cell because  ```y_min > y_max```.

Should I update this tests to assume that the default value for y_min and y_max are the min and max of every cell aligning them with the documented behavior? Or do you have any other suggestions on how to proceed?

In addition, what should be used for ```y_min``` and ```y_max```  when a cell contains only a single value? My current approach is

 -> if ```value >= 0:```  ```y_min = 0``` and ```y_max = value```. 
 -> If ```value < 0:```    ```y_min = value``` and ```y_max = 0```

Would this be the correct way to handle this case?

Thanks!
